\end{align*}

This is the maximal possible sum of the lengths of the arcs which Bunbun traveled, over all possible labelings of the \(2022\) points.

Let the length of each arc be \(l\). Since Bunbun always moves along the shorter arc, the total distance she travels is equal to the sum of the lengths of the arcs between consecutive points in the same direction around the circle. This sum can be calculated as follows:

\begin{align*}
\text{Total distance} &= \sum_{i=1}^{2021} \text{length of arc } P_i P_{i+1} \\
&= \sum_{i=1}^{2021} l \\
&= 2021l
\end{align*}

Since the circumference of the circle is \(2022 \times l\), the fraction of the circumference that Bunbun covers in one hop is \(2021/2022\). The maximal possible sum of the lengths of the arcs occurs when Bunbun covers as much circumference as possible in each hop. This happens when the angle between consecutive points is minimal, which is \(2\pi/2022\). The length of an arc subtending an angle \(\theta\) is given by \(l = \frac{1}{2} \times \text{circumference} \times \theta\). Thus,

\begin{align*}
\text{Maximal total distance} &= \sum_{i=1}^{2022} l \\
&= \sum_{i=1}^{2022} \frac{1}{2} \times 2022l \times \frac{2\pi}{2022} \\
