The maximum size of an independent set in a graph can be found using the famous Hall's Marriage Theorem. In our case, we have 30 students representing vertices and each student having at most 5 friends representing edges. Since every group of 5 students contains a pair that is not friends, the graph is also triangle-free, which is a necessary condition for Hall's Theorem to apply.

Let A be the incidence matrix of the graph. Since each student has at most 5 friends, the degree of each vertex is at most 5, and thus each row of A has at most 5 non-zero entries. The number of students, 30, is equal to the number of vertices, and the number of friends for each student, at most 5, is equal to the maximum degree.

Hall's Theorem states that the maximum size of an independent set in a bipartite graph with b(i) men and w(i) women in the ith partition is equal to min{(S) : S  {1,,i}}. Here, (S) is the size of the smallest subset of women that can be paired with all men in S. In our case, we have b(i) = 1 for all i since each student is considered an individual, and w(i) = 30 - i + 1 since there are 30 students in total and i students have already been taken.

So, the maximum size of an independent set in our graph is:

(S) = min{30 - i + 1 : i  {1,,30}}
= min{31 - i : i  {1,,30}}
= 31 - min{i : i  {1,,30}}
= 31 - 1
= 30

Thus, the maximum number of students who can be not friends is 30.

